Did you know that you can use all 5 of your senses to relieve stress? Our own Nurse Kerry recommends spending some time in the sun. You can also try listening to soothing music or smelling jasmine - which is blooming now in Texas.
You can learn more here: https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/head-games/201502/how-use-all-5-senses-beat-stress

post_text:
Governor Greg Abbott announced an executive order today, April 16, 2020 to close all schools in the state of Texas for the remainder of the 2019-20 academic year. UT Elementary School and UT Charter School, along with all other districts in the state, will comply with this executive order and continue our remote learning that is currently in place for the rest of the school year. Although our buildings remain closed, students will continue to receive instruction and assignments through distant learning for the rest of this academic school year.

This is a difficult time for all of us. We hope and pray that all of you and your loved ones are safe and well. Until next school year, we will see you all in our virtual classrooms and virtual celebrations.
text:
Governor Greg Abbott announced an executive order today, April 16, 2020 to close all schools in the state of Texas for the remainder of the 2019-20 academic year. UT Elementary School and UT Charter School, along with all other districts in the state, will comply with this executive order and continue our remote learning that is currently in place for the rest of the school year. Although our buildings remain closed, students will continue to receive instruction and assignments through distant learning for the rest of this academic school year.

This is a difficult time for all of us. We hope and pray that all of you and your loved ones are safe and well. Until next school year, we will see you all in our virtual classrooms and virtual celebrations.

post_text: We were honored to have UT System Chancellor James W. Milliken and UT Vice President for Diversity and Community Engagement Leonard Moore attend our Donor Appreciation Lunch on April 15. Of course our students provided excellent entertainment that included strings, accordion, Shakespeare and Spanish performances as well as presentations on the Civil Rights Project! And Mr. Pat Oles received the Dan Burck Award for all of his work helping the school with its capital building improvement projects.

post_text: Way to go UT Elementary School and the other award recipients!
shared_text:
Chikage Windler - Meteorologist
November 17, 2017 at 12:24 AM ·

If you know me, you know how much I love Keep Austin Beautiful. My family and I have been volunteers at their events like Clean Sweep and the Lake Travis Clean-up and we look forward to them every year! What fun to serve as emcee for the Beautify Bash at UMLAUF Sculpture Garden & Museum Thursday night while on my CBS Austin dinner break! I had the privilege of announcing the 2017 Annual Award Winners! The Balcones Beautification Award went to Keep Walnut Creek Wild. The Ebay Community Involvement Award went to GoodPop. The Applied Materials Education Award went to The University of Texas Elementary School, the TDS Dennis Hobbs Individual Achievement Award went to Susie Shockley. The Samsung Litter Abatement Award went to The Expedition School, and the Dell Youth Achievement Award went to Jose Garcia-Chong. Congrats to all the winners! Unseasonably warm weather made for a great night under the stars at the Umlauf Sculpture Garden for more than 300 attendees! The event included a silent auction, photo booth, live music from Akina Adderley, games and food. #LoveWhereYouLive

post_text:
PLEASE FORWARD TO ALL UTES 2016 Seniors!

The West Austin Youth Association is now accepting applications for our $4,000 Beyond UT Elementary School scholarship. Current high school seniors who attended UTES, and who will be enrolled as a full time student at the college/university level in the Fall of 2016, are eligible. Deadline is Friday May 6th. The application can be found online at the following link: https://waya.starsscholarshipsonline.com/stars/default.aspx#

Three finalists will be selected from the applications and will be notified by May 20th. Finalists will need to come in for a short 15-20 minute interview. After the interviews, we will select a winner! If you have any questions, please contact Suzanne Starkey, WAYA Finance Director, at 512-473-2528 or at sstarkey@waya.org.

The Healthy Families Initiative @UTElementary was awarded a "Reaching for Excellence Grant" by Texas Health Institute and the Department of State Health Services at yesterday's Texas Action for Healthy Kids Summit.

As one of the HFI projects, this effort aims to increase physical activity through out the school day by providing training and equipment for teachers in order for children to move while learning in the classroom

Special thanks goes to UT Elementary's Schools Nurse Kerin Hurley for being the impetus for this Healthy Families Initiative

post_text: Is your family looking for some spring break learning and fun? The Texas Voices for Healthy Kids team invites your students to join them in Austin on March 18th for Youth Advocacy Day where they will discuss with our lawmakers the importance of access to healthy foods for all Texans! The event is from 11:30 a.m. to 4:00 p.m. and will give students the opportunity to engage in training and to educate their legislators on the importance of increasing the number of grocery stores in communities that need more access to fresh fruits and vegetables. If you are interested, please contact Victoria Nelson at 301-452-9249. Thanks! To learn more about this organization, check them out at: http://www.heart.org/HEARTORG/Advocate/Voices-for-Healthy-Kids_UCM_453195_SubHomePage.jsp

post_text: We are so proud of our Little Longhorn scientists and engineers that took part in the Austin Area Regional Science Fair this past weekend. post_text: Students have been studying issues of social justice in connection to Black History Month. This week our kindergarteners were outraged to learn that "people used to not be able to ride the bus together because of the color of their skin, even if they were friends". Our fifth graders have been connecting issues of social justice and industrialization both with historical and modern events. Second graders are writing biographies on selected civil rights heroes. We have had some amazing conversations about equity and access. Thank you to our amazing teachers for all the work put into making civil rights and the ongoing fight for social justice relevant and meaningful for our students.

post_text: Our students had a great time Friday dressing up for a future career as part of our Career Day. We had astronauts, engineers, surgeons and all three branches of the government represented. What made the day even more special was all the volunteers that gave their time to teach our students about their careers and the education involved in each. Students heard from an astrophysicist, a police officer, a nurse, a financial advisor, a weather reporter, a graphic artist and an engineer to name a few. Thank you friends for making this amazing learning experience possible for our children and thank you Angie Yowell, for creating another successful event for UTES!

post_text: We are incredibly proud to share that our very own third grade teacher, Ms. Mia Tannous has been named the winner of the Lori Tullos Barta Outstanding Educator Award by Down Syndrome Association of Central Texas. He noted through her work that his son has developed not only an increased desire to learn, but more confidence and self-esteem. Thank you Ms. Tannous for all that you do to make an impact on each and every one of your students. Congratulations! http://www.dsact.org/news/2014/7/18/lori-tullos-barta-outstanding-educator-award

post_text: We had a great week and weekend at UTES. Thank you to everyone who made our "Green Day" beautification event a success, even with the rain this weekend. We always love this opportunity to work as a community toward a common goal. We also had a lot of fun learning this week. Students worked on engineering projects with towers and dams in STEAM, conducted interviews to learn about the impact of 9/11, welcomed a new pet, "Sir Fluffy" to the fifth grade and had fun exploring their senses in PK. We also raised $400 towards our Pennies for Peaceful School service learning project. Thank you to our teachers, families, volunteers and students for making this another week to celebrate!

We always love this opportunity to work as a community toward a common goal. We also had a lot of fun learning this week. Students worked on engineering projects with towers and dams in STEAM, conducted interviews to learn about the impact of 9/11, welcomed a new pet, "Sir Fluffy" to the fifth grade and had fun exploring their senses in PK. We also raised $400 towards our Pennies for Peaceful School service learning project. Thank you to our teachers, families, volunteers and students for making this another week to celebrate!

post_text:
Our 5th grade Lil' Longhorn service project this year is to raise $2500 for Nebobongo Primary School in the Democratic Republic of the Congo. This school currently has no water source.

This is our 6th year to partner with a school through H2O For Life. We are excited to help provide clean water and the opportunity for an education to the students at Nebobongo Primary School in Congo.

Please help our Lil' Longhorns provide clean water to the Nebobongo Primary School by either donating or sharing with friends and family.

Hook'em Lil' Longhorns and H2O for Life!

https://secure.commonground.convio.com/h2oforlife/nebobongoprimaryschoolwater/team.html?teamId=a0kE0000003NWa6

post_text:
Okay everyone. It's time for Operation ACTIVATE! Alumni. Our oldest grads will be seniors next year and we have scholarship opportunities for those who are accepted to UT Austin. One is from the Co-Op: a four-year scholarship for the first UT Elementary grad (if there is more than one, an application process will ensue). One that will be given every year from WAYA as well. Problem? We don't know where all our grads are! Please help.

We've identified a few grads who will act as Class Captains to help find and inform their cohort friends about these opportunities, by inviting them to be a part of this group (and we have a Instagram approach being created as well). So if you are a grad, or a parent of a grad, who is interested in being a captain, please let us know right now! Befriend Angie at www.facebook.com/angie.yowell and she'll point you in the right direction.

Thanks.

Would anyone be interested in four plane tickets and a seven-night stay in a beautiful home in Costa Rica? Come to our Bevo Bash next Friday the 16th - at the school from 5 - 8 p.m. The Costa Rica trip is one of many items that will be a part of the silent auction.

Description: Seven night stay in Laura Merritt and JP Kloninger’s 4-bedroom beachside home in Las Catalinas, Costa Rica (sleeps up to 10). Daily housekeeping and daily breakfast cooked in the home is included in the package. Good for within one year of date of auction, subject to availability. The period between December 20, 2014- January 11, 2015 is not included. Onsite amenities and activities include hiking and mountain biking trails, kayaking, snorkeling, paddle boarding, horseback riding. All outdoor equipment can be rented from on-site outfitter. Tours and other services can be arranged through the Las Catalinas concierge.

post_text: Yesterday was a sad day at UTES as we lost our beloved bunny Mario. Mario has been a huge part of our fifth grade team and a special visitor for our younger grades as well. He loved to be held like a baby and have his nose rubbed which was a great way to help him and students feel calm. He will be greatly missed and our fifth graders have been working on his memorial. Our teachers have done a great job of using SEL skills to help our students process this loss. Rest in peace sweet Mario.

post_text: Our UTES accordion students were incredibly excited to perform live at Threadgills this year as part of the 2014 Squeezebox Mania event. Thank you to our amazing accordion teacher, who is also a Grammy award winning musician himself, Mr. Joel Guzman for making this wonderful opportunity possible. Mr. Guzman brought accordion to UTES two years ago so that students would have the opportunity to learn traditional conjunto music. Conjunto, which translated in English means "together", orignated along the Mexico-Texas border in the early 1900's. Joel works with students several days a week and works to organize the Squeezebox Mania event each year, to learn more, check out: http://www.squeezeboxmania.com/about-the-event.html

post_text:
Kindergarten Celebrating Holi. "The colorful festival of Holi is celebrated on Phalgun Purnima which comes in February end or early March. Holi festival has an ancient origin and celebrates the triumph of 'good' over 'bad'. The colorful festival bridges the social gap and renew sweet relationships. On this day, people hug and wish each other 'Happy Holi'."

THANK YOU to the Hindu Student Association at Big UT for helping our students celebrate diversity.

post_text:
Thanks to AJ Bingham, recently awarded Ambassador of the Year by the Greater Austin Black Chamber of Commerce, for speaking with fifth-grade today about advocacy. In preparation for their Walk4Water tomorrow, they were interested in learning how to advocate for those without clean water - and are now inspired!

The kids feel like they now have the tools and know-how to conquer any social issue starting with clean water starting local and going global. Lessons we took away today:
1. Be authentic and honest.
2. Be persistent and respectful.
3. Face-to-face communication is always best.
4. Do what you care about and find strategic alliances.
Wow. You brought a whole new level of knowledge, awareness, and passion to our service learning mission.
